Dialogue: 5,0:19:07.00,0:19:10.20,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{He said stuff about Robin-chan's past, right?}He kept alluding to Robin-{\i1}chan{\i0}'s past.
Dialogue: 5,0:19:10.20,0:19:13.54,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{And he said to us that we'd \Nsomeday regret taking her on.}He also mentioned we'd \Nsomeday regret taking her on.
Dialogue: 5,0:19:13.54,0:19:15.49,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{Now that you mention it...}That rings a bell.
Dialogue: 5,0:19:15.49,0:19:18.76,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{But does that have something to do \Nwith Robin's disappearance?!}But how does this relate \Nto Robin's disappearance?
Dialogue: 5,0:19:19.33,0:19:21.00,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,I don't know.
Dialogue: 5,0:19:21.00,0:19:25.01,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{In any case}Anyway, we're getting nowhere like this. \NLet's go back to the Merry for now.
Dialogue: 5,0:19:26.11,0:19:28.79,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,If there's no problem, she'll be back soon.
Dialogue: 5,0:19:28.79,0:19:30.31,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{Yeah.}Good point.
Dialogue: 5,0:19:49.04,0:19:52.21,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,You can't fix the Merry?! Why not?!
Dialogue: 5,0:19:52.21,0:19:55.34,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,Aren't you guys amazing shipwrights?!
Dialogue: 5,0:19:57.38,0:20:00.29,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{If you're worried about money, look! \NWe've got tons!}If {money's the issue}you need money, just look!\NWe've more than enough!
Dialogue: 5,0:20:00.29,0:20:02.59,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{It has nothing to do with money.}Money's not the issue.
Dialogue: 5,0:20:02.59,0:20:07.10,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{No matter how much you pay, that ship \Ncan't be restored to how she used to be.}All the money in the world can't \Nreturn your ship to its original state.
Dialogue: 5,0:20:08.31,0:20:15.27,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{I'm rather impressed that you guys \Nmade it this far in the state she's in.}I'm rather surprised that your crew made it \Nthis far in a ship that's worse for the wear.
Dialogue: 5,0:20:15.27,0:20:18.69,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,What do you mean?! \NWhat's {going on}wrong with {the }Merry?!
Dialogue: 5,0:20:18.69,0:20:21.82,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,Do you know what {a}the keel is, {shameless girl}you hussy?
Dialogue: 5,0:20:21.82,0:20:23.49,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{The one at the bottom of the ship?}On the bottom of the ship?
Dialogue: 5,0:20:23.49,0:20:27.79,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,That's right.\N{It's the most \Nimportant wood beam on a ship.}It's the most crucial piece of wood on the ship.
Dialogue: 5,0:20:27.79,0:20:31.04,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{It crosses from stem to stern and supports the ship.}It supports the ship from stem to stern.
Dialogue: 5,0:20:31.04,0:20:35.00,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,When you build a ship, \Nyou start off by placing the keel.
Dialogue: 5,0:20:35.00,0:20:40.80,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,Then{,} the stem{ wood}, {stern wood}the stern, and the frame {wood}structure—\N{frame brackets and deck beams...}that'd be the {brackets}floors, futtocks, and deck beams—
Dialogue: 5,0:20:40.80,0:20:45.30,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{We accurately place all those \Npieces of wood around the keel.}and you carefully position\Neach piece of lumber around the keel.
Dialogue: 5,0:20:45.30,0:20:47.49,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{That's how a ship is built.}Shipbuilding in a nutshell.
Dialogue: 5,0:20:47.49,0:20:51.15,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{The keel is the very foundation of a ship's framework. It's the essence of the ship.}The keel is the very foundation—\Nthe very essence—of a ship's framework.
Dialogue: 5,0:20:51.15,0:20:56.81,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{It's not something you can just replace \Nif it takes on a lot of damage...}Once it's damaged beyond repair, \Nit can't just be replaced.
Dialogue: 5,0:20:56.81,0:21:01.03,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{Replacing the keel is the same \Nas building a ship from scratch.}In other words, replacing the keel\Nis essentially building a ship from scratch.
Dialogue: 5,0:21:01.03,0:21:04.09,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,So, no one can fix her anymore.
Dialogue: 5,0:21:04.09,0:21:08.03,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{Your ship is just a collection of wood \Nthat can only await her end.}{Your ship is basically a stack of woodused timber awaiting its endawaiting the eternal dockyardscrapyard.}Your ship is little more than\Nscrap wood awaiting its fate.{Dunno, how's this? -gaijin}{Gaijin, I'm at a loss on how to reword this. Maybe the translation is bad.}
Dialogue: 5,0:21:08.03,0:21:10.45,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,Hey! Don't say it like that!
Dialogue: 5,0:21:11.87,0:21:14.00,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{Not my problem. That's the truth.}{And so?}Whatever. It's the truth.
Dialogue: 5,0:21:16.35,0:21:20.30,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{Then... Then build a ship from scratch for us!}Okay then! You gotta build us a ship from scratch!
Dialogue: 5,0:21:20.30,0:21:22.89,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,Build the Going Merry!
Dialogue: 5,0:21:22.89,0:21:25.19,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{Coo coo! }That's not possible either.
Dialogue: 5,0:21:25.19,0:21:26.22,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{Why not?}But why?!
Dialogue: 5,0:21:26.22,0:21:28.80,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,We can build a similar ship,
Dialogue: 5,0:21:28.80,0:21:32.29,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,but strictly speaking, \N{no one can build the same ship.}it wouldn't be the same as before.
Dialogue: 5,0:21:32.29,0:21:36.23,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{In this world, there are no two ships \Nthat are exactly the same.}The reality is that no two ships can ever be exactly the same.
Dialogue: 5,0:21:36.23,0:21:37.40,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{What does that mean?!}Meaning what?!
Dialogue: 5,0:21:37.40,0:21:41.36,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{Are there any trees in the world \Nthat grow exactly the same way?}Do any two trees ever grow\Nin exactly the same way?
Dialogue: 5,0:21:42.69,0:21:45.49,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,{Sailing ships are mostly made of wood,}A seafaring vessel is built \Nalmost entirely of wood,
Dialogue: 5,0:21:45.49,0:21:49.24,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,so the size and curves of the ship \Nare {all affected}determined by the {shape of the trees.}wood's shape.
Dialogue: 5,0:21:50.04,0:21:55.29,Main-207+,,0,0,0,,That's why an exact duplicate of the ship can't be built,\Neven when using the same blueprint.
